<sections.5>
Genotype-phenotype correlation
he studies on genotype-phenotype analysis show that in most cases the phenotype was similar in patients with deletions and in those with truncating mutations [11,12,18]. atients with large deletions may have a more severe phenotype and additional features [11,25,30,31]. acial gestalt and the psychomotor development delay, particularly of language, are constant. he frequent and severe malformations (, congenital heart defect, agenesis of the corpus callosum) and seizures may lead to suspicion of the diagnosis, but their presence is variable [5,9,12,17,18,22].
he comparison between clinical data concerning the associated malformations of one of the patients with a 695 mutation and those of the other eight patients with the same mutation, demonstrated the phenotypic variability of a single mutation in  [4,12]. his variability is remarkable not only in the same mutation but also in the same family. n fact, two siblings (sister and brother) with characteristic face,  and agenesis of the corpus callosum were discordant for congenital heart disease and ocular coloboma [17]. n the other hand, the phenotypic expression in two affected sisters was very similar for a/hypoplasia of corpus callosum, , congenital heart defect, seizures and microcephaly [18]. hese features might be controlled by common familial genetic modifiers [18].
ew data are available about the parental origin of deletions. he origin of the deleted chromosome is paternal in 17 out of 19 patients examined so far [11,22,25,42]. he investigation of four patients showed that agenesis of corpus callosum (present in two patients and absent in two others) and seizures (present in one patient and absent in three others) showed no correlation with paternal origin of the deletion [11].
