Differential diagnosis
he facial features of patients with  are quite characteristic, but the presence of , epilepsy and mental retardation may initially suggest oldberg-hprintzen syndrome () [5]. he patients with  (actually  609460) share clinical features such as , epilepsy and mental retardation, but have a different facial gestalt (high nasal bridge, synophrys, long curled eyelashes, palpebral ptosis, and cleft palate are commonly observed) [45,46]. he differential diagnosis can be carried out on the basis of facial phenotype and confirmed by mutational analysis of the 2 gene.  patient with short segment , microcephaly, mental retardation, and distinct facial appearance in the absence of 2 intragenic mutations was diagnosed as  [30]. urther molecular studies showed a deletion of the 2q22-q23 region encompassing the 2 gene [31].
